36 SECTION 11. IC 24-16 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE AS
37 A NEW ARTICLE TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
38 JANUARY 1, 2027]:
39 ARTICLE 16. SOCIAL MEDIA PROVIDERS
40 Chapter 1. Applicability
41 Sec. 1. This article does not apply to an adolescent who is legally
42 emancipated.
ES 199—LS 6945/DI 152

20
1 Chapter 2. Definitions
2 Sec. 1. The definitions in this chapter apply throughout this
3 article.
4 Sec. 2. "Adolescent" means an individual who is less than
5 sixteen (16) years of age.
6 Sec. 3. "Daily active users" means the unique users in the
7 United States who:
8 (1) used a particular online forum, website, or application at
9 least eighty percent (80%) of the days during the previous
10 twelve (12) months; or
11 (2) if the online forum, website, or application did not exist
12 during all of the previous twelve (12) months, used the
13 particular online forum, website, or application at least eighty
14 percent (80%) of the days during the previous month.
15 Sec. 4. "Linked account", with respect to a user's account with
16 a social media provider, means another account with the social
17 media provider that the user has designated, through a means
18 provided by the social media provider, as an account:
19 (1) from which the user wishes to receive content;
20 (2) from which the user wishes the social media provider to
21 include in recommendations for content provided to the user
22 by the social media provider; or
23 (3) with which the user wishes to associate the user's account.
24 Sec. 5. (a) "Social media provider" means an online forum,
25 website, or application that satisfies the following criteria:
26 (1) Allows users to upload content or view the content or
27 activity of other users.
28 (2) Has a user base in which ten percent (10%) or more of the
29 daily active users who are less than sixteen (16) years of age
30 spent an average of two (2) hours per day or longer on the
31 online forum, website, or application when using the online
32 forum, website, or application during:
33 (A) the previous twelve (12) months; or
34 (B) if the online forum, website, or application did not exist
35 during all of the previous twelve (12) months, the previous
36 month.
37 (3) Employs algorithms that analyze user data or information
38 on users to select content for users.
39 (4) Has any of the following addictive features:
40 (A) Continuously loading content, or content that loads as
41 the user scrolls down the page without the need to open a
42 separate page.
ES 199—LS 6945/DI 152

21
1 (B) Seamless content, or the use of pages with no visible or
2 apparent end or page breaks.
3 (C) Display of personal interactive metrics that indicate
4 the number of times other users have clicked a button to
5 indicate their reaction to content or have shared or
6 reposted the content.
7 (D) Autoplay video or video that begins to play without the
8 user first clicking on the video or on a play button for the
9 video.
10 (E) Live streaming or a function that allows a user or
11 advertiser to broadcast live video content in real time.
12 (5) Is owned or operated by a person that collectively with any
13 parent, subsidiary, or affiliate of the person, generated at least
14 one billion dollars ($1,000,000,000) in gross revenues,
15 worldwide, in one (1) or more of the immediately preceding
16 three (3) years.
17 (b) The term does not include the following:
18 (1) An online service, website, or application where the
19 exclusive function provides registered users of the service only
20 with the ability to send and receive electronic mail or direct
21 messaging consisting of text, photographs, pictures, images, or
22 videos shared only between the sender and the recipients,
23 without displaying or posting the material publicly or to
24 others not identified as the recipient by the sender.
25 (2) A device manufacturer or application store.
26 (3) An online service, website, or application in which the
27 primary service is on demand audio streaming.
28 (4) A communications service provider (as defined in
29 IC 8-1-2.6-13).
30 Sec. 6. "Transactional data" means a sequence of information
31 that documents an exchange, agreement, or transfer between an
32 individual, commercial entity, or third party used for the purpose
33 of satisfying a request or event. The term includes records that
34 relate to a mortgage, education, or employment.
35 Sec. 7. "Verifiable parental consent" means verifiable parental
36 consent as defined by 15 U.S.C. 6501(9) that is obtained in
37 conformance with 16 CFR 312.5.
38 Chapter 3. Adolescent Use of Social Media
39 Sec. 1. A social media provider that receives a request from an
40 Indiana resident for creation of an account with the social media
41 provider shall comply with the following:
42 (1) The social media provider shall use commercially
ES 199—LS 6945/DI 152

22
1 reasonable means, such as a neutral age screen mechanism, to
2 determine the age and state of residence of the individual
3 requesting creation of the account.
4 (2) If the social media provider determines under subdivision
5 (1) that the individual requesting creation of the account is an
6 adolescent, the social media provider may create the account
7 only if the social media provider receives verifiable parental
8 consent to creation of the account from a parent or legal
9 guardian of the adolescent.
10 Sec. 2. (a) A social media provider shall configure the account
11 as described in subsection (c) of a registered user that the social
12 media provider knows or has reason to know is an:
13 (1) adolescent; and
14 (2) Indiana resident.
15 (b) A social media provider may not allow an adolescent to
16 change or bypass an account configuration described in subsection
17 (c).
18 (c) A social media provider shall configure the account of a
19 registered user described in subsection (a) such that the account
20 does not use or provide, and such that the account holder may not
21 activate or access, the following features or functionality of the
22 social media platform:
23 (1) Functionality to receive direct communications other than
24 direct communications from an account that the user has
25 designated as a linked account.
26 (2) Functionality to appear in the results of a search
27 conducted by a person through the social media provider's
28 search utility unless the person holds an account that the user
29 has designated as a linked account.
30 (3) Dissemination of:
31 (A) content;
32 (B) recommendations for content; or
33 (C) advertising;
34 based on patterns of the adolescent's use of the social media
35 provider.
36 (4) Addictive features described under IC 24-16-2-5(a)(4).
37 (d) The social media provider shall provide the adolescent's
38 parent or legal guardian who provides verifiable parental consent
39 to the creation of the account with the option to receive a separate
40 password for the account that allows the parent or legal guardian
41 to:
42 (1) monitor the amount of time the adolescent spends using
ES 199—LS 6945/DI 152

23
1 the social media platform;
2 (2) set daily and weekly time limits on the adolescent's use of
3 the social media platform;
4 (3) set limits on the times of day during which the adolescent
5 can access the social media platform; and
6 (4) access the adolescent's account at any time.
7 Chapter 4. Continuing Age Estimation
8 Sec. 1. (a) Beginning January 1, 2027, not later than fourteen
9 (14) days after the first date on which an Indiana account holder
10 has spent at least twenty-five (25) hours in a single six (6) month
11 period using a social media provider's social media platform, the
12 social media provider shall:
13 (1) make reasonable efforts; and
14 (2) use reasonable means, taking into consideration the
15 technology and data available to the social media provider;
16 to determine the age of the Indiana account holder.
17 (b) Subject to subsection (d):
18 (1) if a social media provider knows or has reason to know
19 that an Indiana account holder is sixteen (16) years of age or
20 older, the social media provider may consider the Indiana
21 account holder to not be an adolescent for purposes of this
22 article; and
23 (2) if the social media provider knows or has reason to know
24 that the Indiana account holder is not sixteen (16) years of age
25 or older, the social media provider shall consider the Indiana
26 account holder to be an adolescent for purposes of this article.
27 (c) Not later than fourteen (14) days after the first date on which
28 an Indiana account holder has spent at least fifty (50) hours in a
29 single six (6) month period using a social media provider's social
30 media platform, the social media provider shall determine the age
31 of the Indiana account holder as described under subsection (a) for
32 the purpose of verifying the social media provider's determination
33 of the Indiana account holder's age under subsection (a).
34 (d) Subject to subsection (f):
35 (1) if a social media provider knows or has reason to know
36 that an Indiana account holder is sixteen (16) years of age or
37 older, the social media provider may continue to consider the
38 Indiana account holder to not be an adolescent for purposes
39 of this article; and
40 (2) if the social media provider knows or has reason to know
41 that the Indiana account holder is not sixteen (16) years of age
42 or older, the social media provider shall consider the Indiana
ES 199—LS 6945/DI 152

24
1 account holder to be an adolescent for purposes of this article.
2 (e) Subject to subsection (g), a social media provider shall
3 determine the age of an Indiana account holder with the social
4 media provider's social media platform as described under
5 subsection (a) for the purpose of verifying the social media
6 provider's most recent determination of the Indiana account
7 holder's age:
8 (1) when the Indiana account holder has spent an additional
9 one hundred (100) hours using the social media platform
10 following the date on which the social media provider
11 determines the Indiana account holder's age under subsection
12 (c) and each time the Indiana account holder spends an
13 additional one hundred (100) hours using the social media
14 platform thereafter; and
15 (2) each time the social media provider collects demographic
16 information of any kind regarding the Indiana account
17 holder.
18 (f) Subject to subsection (g):
19 (1) if a social media provider knows or has reason to know
20 that an Indiana account holder is sixteen (16) years of age or
21 older, the social media provider may continue to consider the
22 Indiana account holder to not be an adolescent for purposes
23 of this article; and
24 (2) if the social media provider knows or has reason to know
25 that the Indiana account holder is not sixteen (16) years of age
26 or older, the social media provider shall consider the Indiana
27 account holder to be an adolescent for purposes of this article.
28 (g) Once an Indiana account holder has held an account with a
29 social media provider's social media platform continuously for ten
30 (10) consecutive years, the social media provider may, for purposes
31 of the requirements to be met by a social media provider under this
32 article, consider the Indiana account holder to not be an adolescent
33 without determining the age of the Indiana account holder under
34 this section.
35 Sec. 2. (a) This section applies if:
36 (1) a social media provider:
37 (A) determines under section 1 of this chapter; or
38 (B) receives information based on which the social media
39 provider knows or has reason to know;
40 that an Indiana account holder is an adolescent; and
41 (2) the social media provider did not receive verifiable
42 parental consent under IC 24-16-3-1 for creation of the
ES 199—LS 6945/DI 152

25
1 account.
